To save text to a local file in a JavaScript web app, you can use the `FileSaver` API. Here's an example of how to do it:
```
// Get the text you want to save as a string
const text = "Hello World!";

// Create a blob from the text
const blob = new Blob([text], {type: 'text/plain'});

// Save the blob to a local file
FileSaver.saveAs(blob, 'hello_world.txt');
```
This will prompt the user to save the file with the name "hello_world.txt" and the contents of the `text` variable as plain text.

You can also use other libraries like `js-file-downloader` or `FileSaver.js` to achieve this functionality.
```
const download = require('js-file-downloader');

// Get the text you want to save as a string
const text = "Hello World!";

// Create a blob from the text
const blob = new Blob([text], {type: 'text/plain'});

// Save the blob to a local file
download(blob, 'hello_world.txt');
```
You can also use `FileSaver.js` library which is a lightweight library that allows you to save files locally from JavaScript.
```
const FileSaver = require('file-saver');

// Get the text you want to save as a string
const text = "Hello World!";

// Create a blob from the text
const blob = new Blob([text], {type: 'text/plain'});

// Save the blob to a local file
FileSaver.saveAs(blob, 'hello_world.txt');
```
Please note that this will only work in modern browsers and may not work in older versions of Internet Explorer.
